## v1.1.0 (2026-05-24)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus PR #543 — `scripts/run_automation_loop.sh` fan-out argument contract fix
**Verification:** verified-precommit (bash -n + ShellCheck + silent-failure-workaround pre-commit hook all pass; CI gate on PR #543 mergeable but not yet merged at time of writing)

### What changed

- Added new Verified Workflow section 6: "Fan-Out Orchestrator Argument Contract (Auto-Discover vs Required-Arg Phases)"
- Added 3 Failed Attempts rows: (1) trusting shell-header API contract claims, (2) uniform `|| echo "Warning"` swallowing argparse exit 2, (3) the rejected "push auto-discovery into every required-arg main()" approach
- Added new tags: `fan-out`, `argparse`, `orchestrator-contract`, `required-args`
- Extended description with trigger (6): shell orchestrator fan-out where some phases declare `--issues` as `required=True` and others auto-discover
- Added new Verified On row for ProjectHephaestus PR #543
- Added `verification: verified-precommit` frontmatter field (was missing)

### Why

`scripts/run_automation_loop.sh` advertises a 6-phase pipeline (plan → review-plans →
implement → review-prs → address-review → drive-green). Two phases (`planner.main`,
`implementer.main`) auto-discover open issues via `gh_list_open_issues()` when `--issues`
is omitted. The other four declare `--issues … required=True` in argparse with no
fallback. The shell invoked all four uniformly without `--issues`, so each exited with
argparse code 2 every loop. The `|| echo "Warning: <phase> exited non-zero"` clauses
swallowed the failures, and the orchestrator silently reported "complete" while
review-plans / review-prs / address-review / drive-green never did any work — for
months. The operator reported "only planning is running" but actually planning AND
implementation were both working; the four review-style phases were dead.

The fix is a two-tier contract: discover work once per orchestration unit (per repo
per loop) in the shell, then pass via `${ISSUE_ARGS[@]}` to the four required-arg
phases while leaving the auto-discovering phases untouched. Push orchestration
knowledge into the orchestrator, not into the phase.

